From 32e2b46196c7c8b35bb27d17b315c461b98a1478 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Karthikeya <karthi@jovio.in>
Date: Mon, 29 Jun 2026 05:15:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 3/3] feat(supabase): audit_log table for DPDP Section 8
 compliance
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

DPDP Act 2023 Section 8(7) requires data fiduciaries to maintain
records of personal data processing — who accessed what, when,
correction/deletion events, consent grants and withdrawals.

Table design:
- tenant_id, actor_id, actor_email (denormalised — actor_id can go
  null on user deletion but we still need the email for compliance
  audit trails)
- action: text — namespaced strings (auth.signin, call.recording
  .accessed, data.export.requested, etc) documented in the schema
- resource: text — optional, identifies what was acted on
- metadata: jsonb — capped at 8 KB to keep table manageable
- ip + user_agent: request context
- created_at: timestamptz

Three indexes for the common queries: tenant timeline, actor timeline,
action-type filtered.

RLS: users can SELECT their own actor_id rows (DPDP gives them a
right to inspect processing of their data). No INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE
policy — only service-role key (backend) writes here. Prevents users
from forging or scrubbing audit entries.

Retention: schema includes a documented pg_cron snippet to prune
entries older than 24 months. Not auto-enabled because pg_cron is
a Supabase Pro feature; uncomment after upgrading.

Also adds an audit() helper in api-server/src/index.ts that backend
routes can call cleanly. Writes never throw — audit logging must
not break the underlying operation.
---
 supabase/003_audit_log.sql | 94 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 94 insertions(+)
